Questions on Your Selected Data

Choose a dataset and produce the following types of plots and comment on each plot. Plots should be meaningful. If you use the data we used in class, make sure the plots are not the same as the ones in the slides.

library(tidyverse)
df <- read_csv('https://bryantstats.github.io/math421/titanic.csv')
  1. For one continuous variable:
  • Density
df %>% ggplot()+geom_density(mapping = aes(x = Age))
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

  • Histogram
df %>% ggplot()+geom_histogram(mapping = aes(x = Age))
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing non-finite values (stat_bin).

  • Boxplot
df %>% ggplot()+geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(y = Age))
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

  1. For one categorical variable
  • Barplot
df %>% ggplot()+geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = Survived))

  1. For one two continuous variables
  • Scatter Plot
df %>% ggplot()+ geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Age, y = Fare, color = Sex))
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  • Line Plot
df %>% ggplot()+ geom_line(mapping = aes(x = Age, y = Fare, color = Sex))
## Warning: Removed 177 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

  • Smooth Plot
df %>% ggplot()+ geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = Age, y = Fare, color = Sex))
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing non-finite values (stat_smooth).

  1. For one continuous + one categorical variables
  • Density
df %>% ggplot()+ geom_density(mapping = aes(x = Age, color = Sex))
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing non-finite values (stat_density).

  • BoxPlot
df %>% ggplot()+ geom_boxplot(mapping = aes(x = Age, y = Sex))
## Warning: Removed 177 rows containing non-finite values (stat_boxplot).

  1. For two categorical variables: barplot
df %>% ggplot()+ geom_bar(mapping=aes(x=Embarked, fill=Sex), position='dodge')

library(tidyverse)
df <- read_csv('https://raw.githubusercontent.com/govex/COVID-19/master/data_tables/vaccine_data/us_data/time_series/vaccine_data_us_timeline.csv')
  1. Geom_point makes scatter plots, which plot two numeric (or Date) variables. A third categorical variable is often brought in for color. For example, we can compare different vaccine types in Rhode Island by
df %>% filter(Province_State=='Rhode Island') %>% ggplot()+geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Date, y = Doses_admin, color = Vaccine_Type))
## Warning: Removed 200 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Do the follows.

  • Use geom_point to compare the the Moderna and Pfizer vaccine administered in California
df %>% filter(Province_State=='California', Vaccine_Type %in% c('Moderna','Pfizer')) %>% ggplot()+ geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Date, y = Doses_admin, color = Vaccine_Type))
## Warning: Removed 208 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  • Use geom_point to compare the totall vaccine administered in Rhode Island and Massachusetts
df %>% filter(Province_State=='Rhode Island'|Province_State=='Massachusetts', Vaccine_Type=='All') %>% ggplot()+ geom_point(mapping = aes(x = Date, y = Doses_admin, color = Province_State))
## Warning: Removed 13 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  • Change geom_point to geom_line in the above codes to have the corresponding line plots.
df %>% filter(Province_State=='California', Vaccine_Type %in% c('Moderna','Pfizer')) %>% ggplot()+ geom_line(mapping = aes(x = Date, y = Doses_admin, color = Vaccine_Type))
## Warning: Removed 208 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

df %>% filter(Province_State=='Rhode Island'|Province_State=='Massachusetts', Vaccine_Type=='All') %>% ggplot()+ geom_line(mapping = aes(x = Date, y = Doses_admin, color = Province_State))
## Warning: Removed 13 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

  1. Sometime we need to do some calculations on the data before plotting. For example, to compare the popularity of two vaccine Moderna and Pfizer by date, we can use.
# Create a dataset recording these two vaccine administered by date
d1 <- df %>% filter(Vaccine_Type==c('Moderna','Pfizer')) %>% group_by(Date, Vaccine_Type) %>% summarise(vac_admin=mean(Doses_admin, na.rm=TRUE))

# Plot from the newly create data
d1 %>% ggplot()+geom_point(mapping=aes(x=Date, y=vac_admin, color=Vaccine_Type))
## Warning: Removed 14 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

Do the follows.

  • Use geom_point to compare the popularity of all vaccines by date.
d1 <- df %>% group_by(Date, Vaccine_Type) %>% summarise(vac_admin=mean(Doses_admin, na.rm=TRUE))

d1 %>% ggplot()+geom_point(mapping=aes(x=Date, y=vac_admin, color=Vaccine_Type))
## Warning: Removed 22 rows containing missing values (geom_point).

  • Use geom_line to compare the popularity of all vaccines in New England by date.
d2 <- df %>% filter(Province_State %in% c('Massachusetts','Rhode Island','Connecticut','Vermont','New Hampshire','Maine')) %>% group_by(Date, Vaccine_Type) %>% summarise(vac1_admin=mean(Doses_admin, na.rm = TRUE))
d2 %>% ggplot()+geom_line(mapping=aes(x=Date, y=vac1_admin, color=Vaccine_Type))
## Warning: Removed 141 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

  • Use geom_line to compare the popularity of all vaccines in New England by month.
library(lubridate)
df$Month = month(df$Date)
d3 <- df %>% filter(Province_State %in% c('Massachusetts','Rhode Island','Connecticut','Vermont','New Hampshire','Maine')) %>% group_by(Month, Vaccine_Type) %>% summarise(vac1_admin=mean(Doses_admin, na.rm = TRUE))
d3 %>% ggplot()+geom_line(mapping=aes(x=Month, y=vac1_admin, color=Vaccine_Type))
## Warning: Removed 5 row(s) containing missing values (geom_path).

  • Use geom_line to compare states in New England in term of the total vaccine administered by date.
d4 <- df %>% filter(Province_State %in% c('Massachusetts','Rhode Island','Connecticut','Vermont','New Hampshire','Maine')) %>% group_by(Date, Vaccine_Type) %>% summarise(vac_total=sum(Doses_admin, na.rm = TRUE))
d4 %>% ggplot()+geom_line(mapping=aes(x=Date, y=vac_total, color=Vaccine_Type))
